# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: prime-sieve-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] In computational number theory, a variety of algorithms make it possible to generate prime numbers efficiently.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] These are used in various applications, for example hashing, public-key cryptography, and search of prime factors in large numbers.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] For relatively small numbers, it is possible to just apply trial division to each successive odd number.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Prime sieving is the fastest known way to deterministically enumerate the primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] There are some known formulas that can calculate the next prime but there is no known way to express the next prime in terms of the previous primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Also, there is no effective known general manipulation and/or extension of some mathematical expression (even such including later primes) that deterministically calculates the next prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] A prime sieve or prime number sieve is a fast type of algorithm for finding primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] The simple sieve of Eratosthenes (250s BCE), the sieve of Sundaram (1934), the still faster but more complicated sieve of Atkin (2003), sieve of Pritchard (1979), and various wheel sieves are most common.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] A prime sieve works by creating a list of all integers up to a desired limit and progressively removing composite numbers (which it directly generates) until only primes are left.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] This is the most efficient way to obtain a large range of primes; however, to find individual primes, direct primality tests are more efficient.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Furthermore, based on the sieve formalisms, some integer sequences (sequence A240673 in the OEIS) are constructed which also could be used for generating primes in certain intervals.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Historically some prime sieves were realised or partly realised in hardware, including the stencils used by Anton Felkel, Carl Hindenburg and D.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Lehmer as aids to manual computation; and the electromechanical machines, and one later electronic machine, known as the Lehmer sieves by D.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Lehmer (on at least one occasion with D.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Cryptography requires the use of very large primes: for example, with the RSA cryptosystem two primes of at least 1,024 bits (i.e. at least 21023) are recommended.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Even if a composite number is chosen, it will likely be quickly discovered by causing failed operations, except when a Carmichael number happens to be chosen in the case of RSA.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] A less common choice is to use provable primes, which can be generated based on variants of Pocklington primality test, especially Maurer's algorithm.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Both the provable and probable primality tests rely on modular exponentiation.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] In addition with RSA, so-called "strong primes" with both p-1 and p+1 having a large prime factor is preferred, as this is expected to slow down factoring attempts using the Polard's p-1 and Williams' p+1 algorithms.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Such a choice has little effect against elliptic-curve factoring methods, however.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Integers of special forms, such as Mersenne primes or Fermat primes, can be efficiently tested for primality if the prime factorization of *p* − 1 or *p* + 1 is known.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] The sieve of Eratosthenes is generally considered the easiest sieve to implement, but it is not the fastest in the sense of the number of operations for a given range for large sieving ranges.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] In its usual standard implementation (which may include basic wheel factorization for small primes), it can find all the primes up to *N* in time $O(N\log \log N),$ while basic implementations of the sieve of Atkin and wheel sieves run in linear time $O(N)$ .
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Special versions of the Sieve of Eratosthenes using wheel sieve principles can have this same linear $O(N)$ time complexity.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] A special version of the Sieve of Atkin and some special versions of wheel sieves which may include sieving using the methods from the Sieve of Eratosthenes can run in sublinear time complexity of $O(N/\log \log N)$ .
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] The better time complexity special version of the Sieve of Atkin takes space $N^{1/2+o(1)}$ .
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/generation-of-primes] Sorenson shows an improvement to the wheel sieve that takes even less space at $O(N/((\log N)^{L}\log \log N))$ for any $L>1$ .
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] In mathematics, the **prime-counting function** is the function counting the number of prime numbers less than or equal to some real number x.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] It is denoted by *π*(*x*) (unrelated to the number π).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] A symmetric variant seen sometimes is *π*0(*x*), which is equal to *π*(*x*) − 1⁄2 if x is exactly a prime number, and equal to *π*(*x*) otherwise.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] That is, the number of prime numbers less than x, plus half if x equals a prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Of great interest in number theory is the growth rate of the prime-counting function.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] It was conjectured in the end of the 18th century by Gauss and by Legendre to be approximately ${\frac {x}{\log x}}$ where log is the natural logarithm, in the sense that $\lim _{x\rightarrow \infty }{\frac {\pi (x)}{x/\log x}}=1.$ This statement is the prime number theorem.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] An equivalent statement is $\lim _{x\rightarrow \infty }{\frac {\pi (x)}{\operatorname {li} (x)}}=1$ where li is the logarithmic integral function.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The prime number theorem was first proved in 1896 by Jacques Hadamard and by Charles de la Vallée Poussin independently, using properties of the Riemann zeta function introduced by Riemann in 1859.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Proofs of the prime number theorem not using the zeta function or complex analysis were found around 1948 by Atle Selberg and by Paul Erdős (for the most part independently).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] In 1899, de la Vallée Poussin proved that $\pi (x)=\operatorname {li} (x)+O\left(xe^{-a{\sqrt {\log x}}}\right)\quad {\text{as }}x\to \infty$ for some positive constant a.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] More precise estimates of *π*(*x*) are now known.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] For values of x that are not unreasonably large, li(*x*) is greater than *π*(*x*).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] However, *π*(*x*) − li(*x*) is known to change sign infinitely many times.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] For a discussion of this, see Skewes' number.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The Riemann hypothesis suggests that every such non-trivial zero lies along Re(*s*) = ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The table shows how the three functions *π*(*x*), ⁠*x*/log *x*⁠, and li(*x*) compared at powers of 10.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The value for *π*(1024) was originally computed by J.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Kleinjung assuming the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] It was later verified unconditionally in a computation by D.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The value for *π*(1025) is by the same four authors.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The value for *π*(1026) was computed by D.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] All other prior entries in this table were also verified as part of that work.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The values for 1027, 1028, and 1029 were announced by David Baugh and Kim Walisch in 2015, 2020, and 2022, respectively.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] A simple way to find *π*(*x*), if x is not too large, is to use the sieve of Eratosthenes to produce the primes less than or equal to x and then to count them.
