[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] In 1959, Derrick Henry Lehmer extended and simplified Meissel's method.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Define, for real m and for natural numbers n and k, *Pk*(*m*,*n*) as the number of numbers not greater than m with exactly k prime factors, all greater than pn.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] where the sum actually has only finitely many nonzero terms.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Using his method and an IBM 701, Lehmer was able to compute the correct value of *π*(109) and missed the correct value of *π*(1010) by 1.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Further improvements to this method were made by Lagarias, Miller, Odlyzko, Deléglise, and Rivat.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Other prime-counting functions are also used because they are more convenient to work with.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Riemann's prime-power counting function is usually denoted as Π0(*x*) or *J*0(*x*).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] It has jumps of ⁠1/*n*⁠ at prime powers pn and it takes a value halfway between the two sides at the discontinuities of *π*(*x*).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] That added detail is used because the function may then be defined by an inverse Mellin transform.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] where the variable p in each sum ranges over all primes within the specified limits.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Formulas for prime-counting functions come in two kinds: arithmetic formulas and analytic formulas.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Analytic formulas for prime-counting were the first used to prove the prime number theorem.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] They stem from the work of Riemann and von Mangoldt, and are generally known as explicit formulae.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Here ρ are the zeros of the Riemann zeta function in the critical strip, where the real part of ρ is between zero and one.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The formula is valid for values of x greater than one, which is the region of interest.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] The sum over the roots is conditionally convergent, and should be taken in order of increasing absolute value of the imaginary part.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Note that the same sum over the trivial roots gives the last subtrahend in the formula.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/prime-counting-function] Again, the formula is valid for *x* > 1, while ρ are the nontrivial zeros of the zeta function ordered according to their absolute value.
