[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] In mathematics, the **sieve of Atkin** is a modern algorithm for finding all prime numbers up to a specified integer.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Compared with the ancient sieve of Eratosthenes, which marks off multiples of primes, the sieve of Atkin does some preliminary work and then marks off multiples of *squares* of primes, thus achieving a better theoretical asymptotic complexity.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Create a sieve list with an entry for each positive integer; all entries of this list should initially be marked non prime (composite).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] If r is 7, 19, 31, or 43, flip the entry for each possible solution to 3*x*2 + *y*2 = *n*.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] If r is 11, 23, 47, or 59, flip the entry for each possible solution to 3*x*2 − *y*2 = *n* when *x* > *y*.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] If r is something else, ignore it completely.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Start with the lowest number in the sieve list.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Take the next number in the sieve list still marked as being prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Square the number and mark all multiples of that square as non prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Note that the multiples that can be factored by 2, 3, or 5 need not be marked, as these will be ignored in the final enumeration of primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Adding the above ratios of operations together, the above algorithm takes a constant ratio of flipping/marking operations to the sieving range of about 0.2587171021...; From an actual implementation of the algorithm, the ratio is about 0.25 for sieving ranges as low as 67.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] To improve its efficiency, a method must be devised to minimize or eliminate these non-productive computations.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Below is an implementation of the algorithm within Java.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] This makes use of a boolean array to mark integers as being prime, or not.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Worse, the `x` and `y` values are allowed to range up to the limit value rather than limiting them to values less than the limit by large factors resulting a huge increase in computational complexity for redundant operations that do not contribute to the result.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] For these reasons, the above implementation does not show the `O(n)` asymptotic computational complexity of which the algorithm is capable and is not true to the pseudo code above.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] The algorithm completely ignores any numbers with remainder modulo 60 that is divisible by 2, 3, or 5, since numbers with a modulo-60 remainder divisible by one of these three primes are themselves divisible by that prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] All numbers *n* with modulo-sixty remainder 1, 13, 17, 29, 37, 41, 49, or 53 have a modulo-four remainder of 1.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] These numbers are prime if and only if the number of solutions to 4*x*2 + *y*2 = *n* is odd and the number is squarefree (theorem 6.1 of ).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] All numbers *n* with modulo-sixty remainder 7, 19, 31, or 43 have a modulo-six remainder of 1.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] These numbers are prime if and only if the number of solutions to 3*x*2 + *y*2 = *n* is odd and the number is squarefree (theorem 6.2 of ).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] All numbers *n* with modulo-sixty remainder 11, 23, 47, or 59 have a modulo-twelve remainder of 11.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] These numbers are prime if and only if the number of solutions to 3*x*2 − *y*2 = *n* is odd and the number is squarefree (theorem 6.3 of ).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] None of the potential primes are divisible by 2, 3, or 5, so they cannot be divisible by their squares.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] This is why squarefree checks do not include 22, 32, and 52.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Therefore, the algorithm described above can compute primes up to N using *O*(*N*) operations with only *O*(*N*) bits of memory.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] The page-segmented version implemented by the authors has the same *O*(*N*) operations but reduces the memory requirement to just that required by the base primes below the square root of the range of *O*(*N*1/2/log(*N*)) bits of memory plus a minimal page buffer.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] This is slightly better performance with the same memory requirement as the page-segmented sieve of Eratosthenes, which uses *O*(*N* log(log(*N*))) operations and the same *O*(*N*1/2/log(*N*)) bits of memory plus a minimal page buffer.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Thus, even though an optimized implementation may again settle to a *O*(*N*) time complexity, this constant factor of increased time per operations means that the sieve of Atkin is slower.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] A special modified "enumerating lattice points" variation *which is not the above version* of the sieve of Atkin can theoretically compute primes up to *N* using *O*(*N* / log(log(*N*))) operations with *N*1/2+*o*(1) bits of memory, but this variation is rarely implemented.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] That is a little better in performance at a very high cost in memory as compared to both the ordinary page-segmented version and to an equivalent but rarely-implemented version of the sieve of Eratosthenes which uses *O*(*N*) operations and *O*(*N*1/2 log(log(*N*)) / log(*N*)) bits of memory.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Pritchard observed that for the wheel sieves, one can reduce memory consumption while preserving Big-O time complexity, but this generally comes at a cost in an increased constant factor for time per operation due to the extra complexity.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-atkin] Therefore, this special version is likely more of value as an intellectual exercise than a practical prime sieve with reduced real time expended for a given large practical sieving range.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] In mathematics, the **sieve of Eratosthenes** is an ancient algorithm for finding all prime numbers up to any given limit.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] It does so by iteratively marking as composite (i.e., not prime) the multiples of each prime, starting with the first prime number, 2.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The multiples of a given prime are generated as a sequence of numbers starting from that prime, with constant difference between them that is equal to that prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] This is the sieve's key distinction from using trial division to sequentially test each candidate number for divisibility by each prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Once all the multiples of each discovered prime have been marked as composites, the remaining unmarked numbers are primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] One of a number of prime number sieves, it is one of the most efficient ways to find all of the smaller primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] It may be used to find primes in arithmetic progressions.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] A prime number is a natural number that has exactly two distinct natural number divisors: the number 1 and itself.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Initially, let p equal 2, the smallest prime number.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Enumerate the multiples of p by counting in increments of p from 2*p* to n, and mark them in the list (these will be 2*p*, 3*p*, 4*p*, ...; the p itself should not be marked).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Find the smallest number in the list greater than p that is not marked.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Otherwise, let p now equal this new number (which is the next prime), and repeat from step 3.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] When the algorithm terminates, the numbers remaining not marked in the list are all the primes below n.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The main idea here is that every value given to p will be prime, because if it were composite it would be marked as a multiple of some other, smaller prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Note that some of the numbers may be marked more than once (e.g., 15 will be marked both for 3 and 5).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The key property of the sieve is that only additions are needed, no multiplications or divisions are used.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] As a refinement, it is sufficient to mark the numbers in step 3 starting from *p*2, as all the smaller multiples of p will have already been marked at that point.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] This means that the algorithm is allowed to terminate in step 4 when *p*2 is greater than n.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Another refinement is to initially list odd numbers only, (3, 5, ..., *n*), and count in increments of 2*p* in step 3, thus marking only odd multiples of p.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] This actually appears in the original algorithm.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] To find all the prime numbers less than or equal to 30, proceed as follows.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The next number not yet crossed out in the list after 5 is 7; the next step would be to cross out every 7th number in the list after 7, but they are all already crossed out at this point, as these numbers (14, 21, 28) are also multiples of smaller primes because 7 × 7 is greater than 30.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] This algorithm produces all primes not greater than n.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] It includes a common optimization, which is to start enumerating the multiples of each prime i from *i*2.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The time complexity of this algorithm is *O*(*n* log log *n*), provided the array update is an *O*(1) operation, as is usually the case.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] As Sorenson notes, the problem with the sieve of Eratosthenes is not the number of operations it performs but rather its memory requirements.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] For large n, the range of primes may not fit in memory; worse, even for moderate n, its cache use is highly suboptimal.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The algorithm walks through the entire array A, exhibiting almost no locality of reference.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] A solution to these problems is offered by *segmented* sieves, where only portions of the range are sieved at a time.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Find the primes in the first (i.e. the lowest) segment, using the regular sieve.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Mark as non-prime the positions in the array corresponding to the multiples of each prime *p* ≤ √*m* found so far, by enumerating its multiples in steps of *p* starting from the lowest multiple of *p* between m - Δ and m.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The remaining non-marked positions in the array correspond to the primes in the segment.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] It is not necessary to mark any multiples of *these* primes, because all of these primes are larger than √*m*, as for *k* ≥ 1, one has $(k\Delta +1)^{2}>(k+1)\Delta$ .
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] If Δ is chosen to be √*n*, the space complexity of the algorithm is *O*(√*n*), while the time complexity is the same as that of the regular sieve.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] For ranges with upper limit *n* so large that the sieving primes below √*n* as required by the page segmented sieve of Eratosthenes cannot fit in memory, a slower but much more space-efficient sieve like the pseudosquares prime sieve, developed by Jonathan P.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The generation must be initiated only when the prime's square is reached, to avoid adverse effects on efficiency.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] using list comprehension notation with `\` denoting set subtraction of arithmetic progressions of numbers.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Primes can also be produced by iteratively sieving out the composites through divisibility testing by sequential primes, one prime at a time.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] It is not the sieve of Eratosthenes but is often confused with it, even though the sieve of Eratosthenes directly generates the composites instead of testing for them.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Trial division has worse theoretical complexity than that of the sieve of Eratosthenes in generating ranges of primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] When testing each prime, the *optimal* trial division algorithm uses all prime numbers not exceeding its square root, whereas the sieve of Eratosthenes produces each composite from its prime factors only, and gets the primes "for free", between the composites.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The widely known 1975 functional sieve code by David Turner is often presented as an example of the sieve of Eratosthenes but is actually a sub-optimal trial division sieve.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The sieve of Eratosthenes is a popular way to benchmark computer performance.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The time complexity of calculating all primes below n in the random access machine model is *O*(*n* log log *n*) operations, a direct consequence of the fact that the prime harmonic series asymptotically approaches log log *n*.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] It has an exponential time complexity with regard to length of the input, though, which makes it a pseudo-polynomial algorithm.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The basic algorithm requires *O*(*n*) of memory.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The bit complexity of the algorithm is *O*(*n* (log *n*) (log log *n*)) bit operations with a memory requirement of *O*(*n*).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] A special (rarely, if ever, implemented) segmented version of the sieve of Eratosthenes, with basic optimizations, uses *O*(*n*) operations and *O*(√*n*⁠log log *n*/log *n*⁠) bits of memory.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] When implemented with page segmentation in order to save memory, the basic algorithm still requires about *O*(⁠*n*/log *n*⁠) bits of memory (much more than the requirement of the basic page segmented sieve of Eratosthenes using *O*(⁠√*n*/log *n*⁠) bits of memory).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Pritchard's work reduced the memory requirement at the cost of a large constant factor.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Although the resulting wheel sieve has *O*(*n*) performance and an acceptable memory requirement, it is not faster than a reasonably Wheel Factorized basic sieve of Eratosthenes for practical sieving ranges.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Euler's proof of the zeta product formula contains a version of the sieve of Eratosthenes in which each composite number is eliminated exactly once.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] The same sieve was rediscovered and observed to take linear time by Gries & Misra (1978).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] It, too, starts with a list of numbers from 2 to n in order.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] On each step the first element is identified as the next prime, is multiplied with each element of the list (thus starting with itself), and the results are marked in the list for subsequent deletion.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Here the example is shown starting from odds, after the first step of the algorithm.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Thus, when generating a bounded sequence of primes, when the next identified prime exceeds the square root of the upper limit, all the remaining numbers in the list are prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] In the example given above that is achieved on identifying 11 as next prime, giving a list of all primes less than or equal to 80.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/sieve-of-eratosthenes] Note that numbers that will be discarded by a step are still used while marking the multiples in that step, e.g., for the multiples of 3 it is 3 × 3 = 9, 3 × 5 = 15, 3 × 7 = 21, 3 × ***9*** = 27, ..., 3 × ***15*** = 45, ..., so care must be taken dealing with this.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] For example, to find the prime factors of *n* = 70, one can try to divide 70 by successive primes: first, 70 / 2 = 35; next, neither 2 nor 3 evenly divides 35; finally, 35 / 5 = 7, and 7 is itself prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Trial division was first described by Fibonacci in his book *Liber Abaci* (1202).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Given an integer *n* (*n* refers to "the integer to be factored"), the trial division consists of systematically testing whether *n* is divisible by any smaller number.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Clearly, it is only worthwhile to test candidate factors less than *n*, and in order from two upwards because an arbitrary *n* is more likely to be divisible by two than by three, and so on.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] With this ordering, there is no point in testing for divisibility by four if the number has already been determined not divisible by two, and so on for three and any multiple of three, etc.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Therefore, the effort can be reduced by selecting only prime numbers as candidate factors, provided they are repeatedly tested until they fail.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] When a trial division is successful, the process is applied recursively to the resulting quotient.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] A definite bound on the prime factors is possible.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Then the last prime number worth testing as a possible factor of *n* is Pi where *P*2*i* + 1 > *n*; equality here would mean that *P**i* + 1 is a factor.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Thus, testing with 2, 3, and 5 suffices up to *n* = 48 not just 25 because the square of the next prime is 49, and below *n* = 25 just 2 and 3 are sufficient.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Should the square root of *n* be an integer, then it is a factor and *n* is a perfect square.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Determining the primes less than or equal to ${\sqrt {n}}$ is not a trivial task as *n* gets larger, so the simplest computer programs to factor a number just try successive integers, prime and composite, from 2 to ${\sqrt {n}}$ as possible factors.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] In the worst case, trial division is a laborious algorithm.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] trial divisions, where $\pi (x)$ denotes the prime-counting function, the number of primes less than *x*.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] This does not take into account the overhead of primality testing to obtain the prime numbers as candidate factors.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] A useful table need not be large: P(3512) = 32749, the last prime that fits into a sixteen-bit signed integer and P(6542) = 65521 for unsigned sixteen-bit integers.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] That would suffice to test primality for numbers up to 655372 = 4,295,098,369.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Preparing such a table (usually via the Sieve of Eratosthenes) would only be worthwhile if many numbers were to be tested.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] In both cases, the required time grows exponentially with the digits of the number.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Even so, this is a quite satisfactory method, considering that even the best-known algorithms have exponential time growth.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] For *a* chosen uniformly at random from integers of a given length, there is a 50% chance that 2 is a factor of *a* and a 33% chance that 3 is a factor of *a*, and so on.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] It can be shown that 88% of all positive integers have a factor under 100 and that 92% have a factor under 1000.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Thus, when confronted by an arbitrary large *a*, it is worthwhile to check for divisibility by the small primes, since for $a=1000$ , in base-2 $n=10$ .
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] However, many-digit numbers that do not have factors in the small primes can require days or months to factor with trial division.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] In such cases other methods are used such as the quadratic sieve and the general number field sieve (GNFS).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] Because these methods also have superpolynomial time growth a practical limit of *n* digits is reached very quickly.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] For this reason, in public key cryptography, values for *a* are chosen to have large prime factors of similar size so that they cannot be factored by any publicly known method in a useful time period on any available computer system or computer cluster such as supercomputers and computer grids.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/trial-division] The largest cryptography-grade number that has been factored is RSA-250, a 250-digit number, using the GNFS and resources of several supercomputers.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] For a chosen number n (usually no larger than 4 or 5), the first *n* primes determine the specific way to generate a sequence of natural numbers which are all known in advance to be coprime with these primes; that is, they are all known to not be multiples of any of these primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] This method can thus be used for an improvement of the trial division method for integer factorization, as none of the generated numbers need be tested in trial divisions by those small primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The trial division method consists of dividing the number to be factorized by the integers in increasing order (2, 3, 4, 5, ...) successively.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] A common improvement consists of testing only by primes, i.e. by 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, ….
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] With the wheel factorization, one starts from a small list of numbers, called the *basis* (usually the first few primes); then, one generates the list, called the *wheel*, of the integers that are coprime with all the numbers in the basis.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Then, for the numbers generated by "rolling the wheel", one needs to only consider the primes *not* in the basis as their possible factors.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] It is as if these generated numbers have already been tested, and found to not be divisible by any of the primes in the basis.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] It is an optimization because all these operations become redundant, and are spared from being performed at all.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] When used in finding primes, or sieving in general, this method reduces the amount of candidate numbers to be considered as possible primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] With the basis {2, 3}, the reduction is to 1/3 < 34% of all the numbers.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] This means that fully 2/3 of all the candidate numbers are skipped over automatically.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Larger bases reduce this proportion even further; for example, with basis {2, 3, 5} to 8/30 < 27%, and with basis {2, 3, 5, 7} to 48/210 < 23%.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The bigger the wheel, the larger the computational resources involved and the smaller the additional improvements, leading to quickly diminishing returns.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Every second number thus generated will be even.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Every second number in these triplets will be a multiple of 3, because numbers of the form 3 + 6k are all odd multiples of 3.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] This is the closest it comes to the *rolling the wheel* metaphor.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The second turn is obtained by adding 30, the product of the basis, to the numbers in the first turn.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The third turn is obtained by adding 30 to the second turn, and so on.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The suggested implementation that follows uses an auxiliary function div(n,k), which tests whether n is evenly divisible by k, and returns *true* in this case and *false* otherwise.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] In this implementation, the number to be factorized is n, and the program returns the smallest divisor of n – returning n itself if it is prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] For getting the complete factorization of an integer, the computation may be continued without restarting the wheel at the beginning.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] This leads to the following program for a complete factorization, where the function add adds its first argument at the end of the second argument, which must be a list.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Wheel factorization is used for generating lists of mostly prime numbers from a simple mathematical formula and a much smaller list of the first prime numbers.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] These lists may then be used in trial division or sieves.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Because not all the numbers in these lists are prime, doing so introduces inefficient redundant operations.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] However, the generators themselves require very little memory compared to keeping a pure list of prime numbers.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The small list of initial prime numbers constitute complete parameters for the algorithm to generate the remainder of the list.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] These generators are referred to as **wheels**.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] While each wheel may generate an infinite list of numbers, past a certain point, the numbers cease to be mostly prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The method may further be applied recursively as a prime number **wheel sieve** to generate more accurate wheels.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Much definitive work on wheel factorization, sieves using wheel factorization, and wheel sieve, was done by Paul Pritchard in formulating a series of different algorithms.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] To visualize the use of a factorization wheel, one may start by writing the natural numbers around circles as shown in the adjacent diagram.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The number of spokes is chosen such that prime numbers will have a tendency to accumulate in a minority of the spokes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Multiply the base prime numbers together to give the result n, which is the circumference of the factorization wheel.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] This will be the inner-most circle representing one rotation of the wheel.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] From the numbers 1 to *n* in the innermost circle, strike off all multiples of the base primes from step one as applied in step 2.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] This composite number elimination can be accomplished either by use of a sieve such as the Sieve of Eratosthenes or as the result of applications of smaller factorization wheels.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Taking x to be the number of circles written so far, continue to write *xn* + 1 to *xn* + *n* in concentric circles around the inner-most circle, such that *xn* + 1 is in the same position as (*x* − 1)*n* + 1.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Repeat step 5 until the largest rotation circle spans the largest number to be tested for primality.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Strike off the spokes of the prime numbers as found in step 1 and applied in step 2 in all outer circles without striking off the prime numbers in the inner-most circle (in circle 1).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Strike off the spokes of all multiples of prime numbers struck from the inner circle 1 in step 4 in the same way as striking off the spokes of the base primes in step 8.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The remaining numbers in the wheel are mostly prime numbers (they are collectively called "relatively" prime).
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Use other methods such as the Sieve of Eratosthenes or further application of larger factorization wheels to remove the remaining non-primes.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The resulting list contains a non-prime number of 25 which is 52.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The elimination of composite numbers by a factorization wheel is based on the following: Given a number *k* > *n*, we know that k is not prime if *k* mod *n* and n are not relatively prime.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] From that, the fraction of numbers that the wheel sieve eliminates can be determined (although not all need be physically struck off; many can be culled automatically in the operations of copying of lesser wheels to greater wheels) as 1 − *φ*(*n*) / *n*, which is also the efficiency of the sieve.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Thus *φ*(*n*) / *n* goes to zero slowly as n increases to infinity, and it can be seen that this efficiency rises very slowly to 100% for infinitely large n.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] To be of maximum use on a computer, we want the numbers that are smaller than n and relatively prime to it as a set.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The following sets are *S*2 = {1}, which means that it starts at 3 for all odd numbers with the factors of 2 eliminated (circumference of 2), *S*6 = {1,5} has the factors of 2 and 3 eliminated (circumference of 6) as for the initial base wheel in the example above, and so on.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] Let *S**n* + *k* be the set where k has been added to each element of *S**n*.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] 1 and *p**i*+1 will be the two smallest of *S**n* when *n* > 2, removing the need to compute prime numbers separately, although the algorithm does need to keep a record of all eliminated base primes which are no longer included in the succeeding sets.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] All sets where the circumference *n* > 2 are symmetrical around *n* / 2, reducing storage requirements.
[src:prime-sieve-algorithms/wheel-factorization] The following algorithm does not use this fact, but it is based on the fact that the gaps between successive numbers in each set are symmetrical around the halfway point.
